text:
Touch
Take a strip of paper. Fold it in half. Fold it in half again. Open it. You should see four equal parts.
Now mark the strip like a number line: write 0 at the left edge, 1 at the right edge. The fold creases are sitting at \tfrac{1}{4}, \tfrac{1}{2}, \tfrac{3}{4}.
Move the slider below to drop a marker on your strip. Watch how the same point has many names.

viewof q = Inputs.range([-2, 2], {value: 0.5, step: 0.05, label: "Pick a point"})







{
  const x = q;
  const approx = (a, b) =&gt; Math.abs(a - b) &lt; 1e-9;
  const candidates = [];
  for (let d = 1; d &lt;= 12; d++) {
    const n = Math.round(x * d);
    if (approx(n / d, x)) candidates.push(`${n}/${d}`);
  }
  const decimal = x.toFixed(2);
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.6;"&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;Decimal:&lt;/b&gt; ${decimal}&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;As a fraction (many names):&lt;/b&gt; ${candidates.slice(0,4).join(", ") || "doesn't land cleanly here"}&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-top:0.6rem;color:#666;font-size:0.95rem;"&gt;
      Many fractions, the same point. The point is more fundamental than its names.
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Drag through positive and negative values. Notice three things: the same point can be written as \tfrac{2}{4} or \tfrac{1}{2}; some points have short decimal names; and the negative side mirrors the positive side exactly.

Touch
Take a sheet of squared graph paper, or imagine one. Colour in a 1
\times 1 square. Now a 2 \times 2. Now a 3 \times 3. Count the unit squares in each.
If no graph paper, the slider below builds them for you.

viewof n = Inputs.range([1, 12], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "Side length n"})







{
  const cells = [];
  const sz = 22;
  for (let i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)
    for (let j = 0; j &lt; n; j++)
      cells.push(`&lt;rect x="${j*sz}" y="${i*sz}" width="${sz-2}" height="${sz-2}" fill="#bde0fe" stroke="#1d4ed8"/&gt;`);
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;"&gt;
    &lt;svg width="${n*sz+2}" height="${n*sz+2}"&gt;${cells.join("")}&lt;/svg&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-top:0.4rem;color:#444;"&gt;
      side length &lt;b&gt;${n}&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp; - &nbsp; total cells &lt;b&gt;${n*n}&lt;/b&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Slide n from 1 up to 12. Watch the cell count: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25,
36, \ldots Now play the game in reverse: if I tell you a square has 49 cells, what was its side?

Touch
Find a sheet of squared graph paper, or imagine one. Draw a horizontal line across the middle and a vertical line down the middle. Where they cross, write 0. To the right of the cross, mark 1, 2, 3, \ldots. Going up, mark 1, 2, 3, \ldots.
Pick a place on the paper. How would you tell a friend where it is, just using two numbers?
The slider below shows the same idea.

viewof px = Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 4, step: 1, label: "Across (x)"})
viewof py = Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 3, step: 1, label: "Up (y)"})
















{
  const k = 30;
  const margin = 25;
  const cells = [];
  for (let i = 0; i &lt;= 10; i++) {
    cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${margin+i*k}" y1="${margin}" x2="${margin+i*k}" y2="${margin+10*k}" stroke="#eee"/&gt;`);
    cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${margin}" y1="${margin+i*k}" x2="${margin+10*k}" y2="${margin+i*k}" stroke="#eee"/&gt;`);
  }
  cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${margin}" y1="${margin}" x2="${margin}" y2="${margin+10*k}" stroke="#333" stroke-width="1.5"/&gt;`);
  cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${margin}" y1="${margin+10*k}" x2="${margin+10*k}" y2="${margin+10*k}" stroke="#333" stroke-width="1.5"/&gt;`);
  const cx = margin + px*k;
  const cy = margin + (10-py)*k;
  cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${margin}" y1="${cy}" x2="${cx}" y2="${cy}" stroke="#1d4ed8" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/&gt;`);
  cells.push(`&lt;line x1="${cx}" y1="${margin+10*k}" x2="${cx}" y2="${cy}" stroke="#1d4ed8" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/&gt;`);
  cells.push(`&lt;circle cx="${cx}" cy="${cy}" r="6" fill="#dc2626"/&gt;`);
  cells.push(`&lt;text x="${cx+10}" y="${cy-6}" font-size="13" font-family="system-ui"&gt;(${px}, ${py})&lt;/text&gt;`);
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;"&gt;
    &lt;svg width="${margin*2 + 10*k}" height="${margin*2 + 10*k}" style="background:#fafafa;"&gt;
      ${cells.join("")}
    &lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Slide the two numbers. The red dot moves. Two numbers determine a position. The first says across; the second says up. They are not interchangeable.

Touch
Open your kitchen and find a recipe. “Tea for 4 people: 800 ml water.” You’re hosting 6 people instead.
The widget below scales the recipe.

viewof people = Inputs.range([1, 12], {value: 4, step: 1, label: "People"})







{
  const baseP = 4;
  const baseW = 800; // ml water
  const baseT = 8;   // g tea leaves
  const baseM = 200; // ml milk
  const factor = people / baseP;
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;font-size:1.05rem;line-height:1.6;"&gt;
    &lt;table style="border-collapse:collapse;"&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;&lt;th style="text-align:left;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;Ingredient&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;For 4&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;For ${people}&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style="padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;Water&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${baseW} ml&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${(baseW*factor).toFixed(0)} ml&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style="padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;Tea leaves&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${baseT} g&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${(baseT*factor).toFixed(1)} g&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style="padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;Milk&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${baseM} ml&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="text-align:right;padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;"&gt;${(baseM*factor).toFixed(0)} ml&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Slide the people count from 4 to 12. Every ingredient triples together. They march in step. Now imagine a different problem: you have 24 litres of paint, enough to paint one wall in 3 days. With twice the painters, half the time. Two quantities, but moving in opposite directions.

Touch
If you have a set of children’s blocks (or sugar cubes), build a 2 \times 2 \times 2 cube. Count how many small cubes you used. Now build a 3 \times 3 \times 3. Count again.
If no blocks, the slider below assembles them.

viewof n3 = Inputs.range([1, 6], {value: 3, step: 1, label: "Side n"})







{
  const n = n3;
  const sz = 18;
  const off = 8;
  const layers = [];
  for (let k = 0; k &lt; n; k++) {
    const cells = [];
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)
      for (let j = 0; j &lt; n; j++) {
        const x = j*sz + k*off;
        const y = i*sz + (n-1-k)*off;
        cells.push(`&lt;rect x="${x}" y="${y}" width="${sz-2}" height="${sz-2}" fill="#bde0fe" stroke="#1d4ed8" opacity="${1 - k*0.08}"/&gt;`);
      }
    layers.push(cells.join(""));
  }
  const total = n*n*n;
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;"&gt;
    &lt;svg width="${n*sz + n*off + 4}" height="${n*sz + n*off + 4}"&gt;${layers.join("")}&lt;/svg&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-top:0.4rem;color:#444;"&gt;
      side &lt;b&gt;${n}&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp; - &nbsp; little cubes used &lt;b&gt;${total}&lt;/b&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Slide n from 1 up to 6. The counts go 1, 8, 27, 64, 125, 216. Reverse the game: I tell you a cube was built from 343 little cubes, what was its side?

Touch
Roll a single die — a real one if you have it, or a coin flipped six times if you don’t. Tally the number of times each face came up. Now roll it five more times.
If you don’t have a die, the slider below rolls one for you.

viewof rolls = Inputs.range([6, 600], {value: 30, step: 6, label: "How many rolls?"})
viewof seed = Inputs.button("Re-roll")
















{
  seed; // dependency on the button
  const counts = [0,0,0,0,0,0];
  for (let i = 0; i &lt; rolls; i++) counts[Math.floor(Math.random()*6)]++;
  const max = Math.max(...counts);
  const fracs = counts.map(c =&gt; (c / rolls).toFixed(2));
  const bars = counts.map((c,i) =&gt;
    `&lt;div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;margin:0.15rem 0;"&gt;
       &lt;div style="width:1.5rem;text-align:right;"&gt;${i+1}&lt;/div&gt;
       &lt;div style="background:#bde0fe;height:1rem;width:${(c/Math.max(max,1))*240}px;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
       &lt;div style="color:#666;font-size:0.9rem;"&gt;${c} (${fracs[i]})&lt;/div&gt;
     &lt;/div&gt;`).join("");
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;font-size:1rem;"&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-bottom:0.4rem;color:#444;"&gt;Faces 1 - 6, count and fraction:&lt;/div&gt;
    ${html`&lt;div&gt;${bars}&lt;/div&gt;`.replace(/&lt;/g,"&lt;")}
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Push the slider from 30 rolls to 300 rolls. Press Re-roll a few times. Watch the fractions. What do they do?

Touch
A staircase. Each step is the same height. You climb steadily.
Stand at the bottom (step 0). Each next step adds d centimetres of height. After n steps, your height above the floor is…

viewof a = Inputs.range([0, 30], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "Starting height a (cm)"})







viewof d = Inputs.range([1, 25], {value: 15, step: 1, label: "Step height d (cm)"})







viewof n = Inputs.range([1, 12], {value: 6, step: 1, label: "Step number n"})







{
  const w = 380, h = 300, padX = 30, padY = 20;
  const stepW = (w - 2 * padX) / 12;
  const yMax = a + 12 * d;
  const yS = d3.scaleLinear().domain([0, yMax]).range([h - padY, padY]);
  const svg = d3.create("svg").attr("width", w).attr("height", h)
    .style("background", "#fafafa").style("border", "1px solid #ddd");
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", padX).attr("x2", w - padX)
    .attr("y1", yS(0)).attr("y2", yS(0)).attr("stroke", "#888");
  for (let i = 1; i &lt;= 12; i++) {
    const top = a + i * d;
    const x = padX + (i - 0.5) * stepW;
    svg.append("rect").attr("x", x - stepW * 0.4).attr("y", yS(top))
      .attr("width", stepW * 0.8).attr("height", yS(0) - yS(top))
      .attr("fill", i &lt;= n ? "#26a" : "#ddd").attr("stroke", "#333");
    svg.append("text").attr("x", x).attr("y", yS(0) + 14)
      .attr("text-anchor", "middle").attr("font-size", 10).text(i);
  }
  const tn = a + (n - 1) * d;
  svg.append("text").attr("x", padX).attr("y", padY + 14)
    .attr("font-size", 13).text(`Top of step n=${n}: a + (n-1)d = ${tn} cm`);
  return svg.node();
}






The heights of step tops are: a + d,\ a + 2d,\ a + 3d, \ldots. Add the same thing each time.

Touch
Two friends are at points A = (1, 2) and B = (5, 5) on a flat field. Use the widget — drag B — and watch how the distance between them changes.

viewof bx = Inputs.range([-5, 9], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "B's x"})







viewof by = Inputs.range([-5, 9], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "B's y"})







{
  const w = 380, h = 320, padX = 30, padY = 20;
  const xS = d3.scaleLinear().domain([-6, 10]).range([padX, w - padX]);
  const yS = d3.scaleLinear().domain([-6, 10]).range([h - padY, padY]);
  const A = [1, 2], B = [bx, by];
  const svg = d3.create("svg").attr("width", w).attr("height", h)
    .style("background", "#fafafa").style("border", "1px solid #ddd");
  // grid
  for (let i = -6; i &lt;= 10; i++) {
    svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(i)).attr("x2", xS(i))
      .attr("y1", yS(-6)).attr("y2", yS(10)).attr("stroke", "#eee");
    svg.append("line").attr("y1", yS(i)).attr("y2", yS(i))
      .attr("x1", xS(-6)).attr("x2", xS(10)).attr("stroke", "#eee");
  }
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(-6)).attr("x2", xS(10))
    .attr("y1", yS(0)).attr("y2", yS(0)).attr("stroke", "#888");
  svg.append("line").attr("y1", yS(-6)).attr("y2", yS(10))
    .attr("x1", xS(0)).attr("x2", xS(0)).attr("stroke", "#888");
  // right triangle
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(A[0])).attr("y1", yS(A[1]))
    .attr("x2", xS(B[0])).attr("y2", yS(A[1])).attr("stroke", "#26a")
    .attr("stroke-dasharray", "3,3");
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(B[0])).attr("y1", yS(A[1]))
    .attr("x2", xS(B[0])).attr("y2", yS(B[1])).attr("stroke", "#26a")
    .attr("stroke-dasharray", "3,3");
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(A[0])).attr("y1", yS(A[1]))
    .attr("x2", xS(B[0])).attr("y2", yS(B[1])).attr("stroke", "#c33")
    .attr("stroke-width", 2);
  // points
  for (const [P, name] of [[A, "A"], [B, "B"]]) {
    svg.append("circle").attr("cx", xS(P[0])).attr("cy", yS(P[1]))
      .attr("r", 4).attr("fill", "#333");
    svg.append("text").attr("x", xS(P[0]) + 6).attr("y", yS(P[1]) - 6)
      .attr("font-size", 12).text(`${name}(${P[0]}, ${P[1]})`);
  }
  const dx = B[0] - A[0], dy = B[1] - A[1];
  const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy);
  svg.append("text").attr("x", padX).attr("y", h - 6).attr("font-size", 13)
    .text(`Δx = ${dx},  Δy = ${dy},  distance = √(${dx*dx} + ${dy*dy}) = ${dist.toFixed(3)}`);
  return svg.node();
}






The dashed lines show the horizontal and vertical “legs” of a right triangle whose hypotenuse is AB. The horizontal leg has length |x_2
- x_1|, the vertical leg |y_2 - y_1|.

Touch
A pencil. The body is a cylinder; the sharpened tip is a cone. Pencil = cylinder + cone (glued along a flat face).
A capsule (the medicine kind). The middle is a cylinder; the two end caps are hemispheres of a sphere. Capsule = cylinder + 2 hemispheres.

viewof shape = Inputs.select(["pencil (cylinder + cone)", "capsule (cylinder + 2 hemispheres)", "ice-cream (cone + hemisphere)"], {label: "Composite shape"})







viewof rad12 = Inputs.range([1, 5], {value: 2, step: 0.5, label: "Radius r (cm)"})







viewof len12 = Inputs.range([2, 12], {value: 6, step: 1, label: "Cylinder length / cone height (cm)"})







{
  const r = rad12, L = len12;
  let report;
  if (shape === "pencil (cylinder + cone)") {
    const Vcyl = Math.PI * r * r * L;
    const Vcone = Math.PI * r * r * L / 3;
    const Vtot = Vcyl + Vcone;
    report = `Pencil volume = πr²L + (1/3)πr²L = ${Vtot.toFixed(2)} cm³`;
  } else if (shape === "capsule (cylinder + 2 hemispheres)") {
    const Vcyl = Math.PI * r * r * L;
    const Vsph = (4 / 3) * Math.PI * r * r * r;
    const Vtot = Vcyl + Vsph;
    report = `Capsule volume = πr²L + (4/3)πr³ = ${Vtot.toFixed(2)} cm³`;
  } else {
    const Vcone = Math.PI * r * r * L / 3;
    const Vhemi = (2 / 3) * Math.PI * r * r * r;
    const Vtot = Vcone + Vhemi;
    report = `Ice-cream volume = (1/3)πr²L + (2/3)πr³ = ${Vtot.toFixed(2)} cm³`;
  }
  return html`&lt;pre style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 13px;"&gt;${report}
r = ${r} cm, L = ${L} cm&lt;/pre&gt;`;
}






The recipe: identify the parts, compute each volume separately, then add. The same applies to surface area — but be careful: glued faces disappear from the outside.

Touch
Two paper strips. On each, one straight line is drawn. Slide one over the other and ask: where do they touch? Sometimes one point. Sometimes — when the strips are parallel — never. Sometimes — when the lines coincide — everywhere along the strip.
Try the widget. Two lines, two equations: a_1 x + b_1 y = c_1, \qquad a_2 x + b_2 y = c_2.

viewof a1 = Inputs.range([-3, 3], {value: 1, step: 0.5, label: "a₁"})







viewof b1 = Inputs.range([-3, 3], {value: 1, step: 0.5, label: "b₁"})







viewof c1 = Inputs.range([-6, 6], {value: 4, step: 1, label: "c₁"})







viewof a2 = Inputs.range([-3, 3], {value: 2, step: 0.5, label: "a₂"})







viewof b2 = Inputs.range([-3, 3], {value: -1, step: 0.5, label: "b₂"})







viewof c2 = Inputs.range([-6, 6], {value: 1, step: 1, label: "c₂"})







{
  const w = 420, h = 280, padX = 30, padY = 30;
  const xMin = -6, xMax = 6, yMin = -6, yMax = 6;
  const xS = d3.scaleLinear().domain([xMin, xMax]).range([padX, w - padX]);
  const yS = d3.scaleLinear().domain([yMin, yMax]).range([h - padY, padY]);
  const svg = d3.create("svg").attr("width", w).attr("height", h)
    .style("background", "#fafafa").style("border", "1px solid #ddd");
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", padX).attr("x2", w - padX)
    .attr("y1", yS(0)).attr("y2", yS(0)).attr("stroke", "#bbb");
  svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(0)).attr("x2", xS(0))
    .attr("y1", padY).attr("y2", h - padY).attr("stroke", "#bbb");
  function drawLine(a, b, c, color) {
    if (Math.abs(b) &gt; 1e-9) {
      const y1 = (c - a * xMin) / b;
      const y2 = (c - a * xMax) / b;
      svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(xMin)).attr("y1", yS(y1))
        .attr("x2", xS(xMax)).attr("y2", yS(y2))
        .attr("stroke", color).attr("stroke-width", 2);
    } else if (Math.abs(a) &gt; 1e-9) {
      const x = c / a;
      svg.append("line").attr("x1", xS(x)).attr("y1", padY)
        .attr("x2", xS(x)).attr("y2", h - padY)
        .attr("stroke", color).attr("stroke-width", 2);
    }
  }
  drawLine(a1, b1, c1, "#26a");
  drawLine(a2, b2, c2, "#c33");
  // intersection
  const det = a1 * b2 - a2 * b1;
  let label = "";
  if (Math.abs(det) &lt; 1e-9) {
    // parallel or coincident
    if (Math.abs(a1 * c2 - a2 * c1) &lt; 1e-9 && Math.abs(b1 * c2 - b2 * c1) &lt; 1e-9) {
      label = "Coincident — infinitely many solutions";
    } else {
      label = "Parallel — no solution";
    }
  } else {
    const x = (c1 * b2 - c2 * b1) / det;
    const y = (a1 * c2 - a2 * c1) / det;
    label = `Intersection: (${x.toFixed(2)}, ${y.toFixed(2)})`;
    svg.append("circle").attr("cx", xS(x)).attr("cy", yS(y))
      .attr("r", 5).attr("fill", "#0a7");
  }
  svg.append("text").attr("x", padX).attr("y", h - 6)
    .attr("font-size", 13).text(label);
  return svg.node();
}






Set a_1 = 1, b_1 = 1, c_1 = 4 and a_2 = 2, b_2 = 2, c_2 = 8 — what happens? Set a_2 = 2, b_2 = 2, c_2 = 6 — what happens now?

Touch
A class of 30 students; their marks (out of 50) on a test are listed. Imagine all 30 marks. The questions a teacher asks:

“What is the typical mark?” → Mean.
“What is the middle mark — half above, half below?” → Median.
“Which mark appears most often?” → Mode.

Drag the slider — generate a class — see all three.

viewof seed = Inputs.range([1, 20], {value: 4, step: 1, label: "Random class (seed)"})







{
  // simple deterministic pseudo-random
  function rng(s) { let x = s; return () =&gt; { x = (x * 9301 + 49297) % 233280; return x / 233280; }; }
  const r = rng(seed);
  const marks = [];
  for (let i = 0; i &lt; 30; i++) {
    marks.push(Math.floor(r() * 50) + 1);
  }
  marks.sort((a, b) =&gt; a - b);
  const mean = marks.reduce((s, m) =&gt; s + m, 0) / 30;
  const median = (marks[14] + marks[15]) / 2;
  const counts = {};
  for (const m of marks) counts[m] = (counts[m] || 0) + 1;
  let mode, modeC = 0;
  for (const k in counts) if (counts[k] &gt; modeC) { modeC = counts[k]; mode = k; }
  return html`&lt;pre style="font-size: 12px; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;"&gt;
Sorted marks: ${marks.join(", ")}

Mean    = sum / n  = ${mean.toFixed(2)}
Median  = avg of 15th and 16th = ${median.toFixed(2)}
Mode    = most-frequent value  = ${mode} (appears ${modeC} times)
&lt;/pre&gt;`;
}






The three numbers are rarely all the same. They tell different stories about the same data.

Touch
A pizza, cut from the centre. One slice. The two straight edges of the slice are radii of the circle; the curved edge is an arc; the angle between the two radii is the sector angle.

viewof rad = Inputs.range([1, 10], {value: 5, step: 0.5, label: "Radius r (cm)"})







viewof secAngle = Inputs.range([10, 360], {value: 60, step: 10, label: "Sector angle θ (°)"})







{
  const w = 320, h = 320, cx = w / 2, cy = h / 2;
  const r = rad * 25;
  const θ = secAngle * Math.PI / 180;
  const x1 = cx + r * Math.cos(0), y1 = cy + r * Math.sin(0);
  const x2 = cx + r * Math.cos(θ), y2 = cy + r * Math.sin(θ);
  const largeArc = θ &gt; Math.PI ? 1 : 0;
  const path = `M ${cx},${cy} L ${x1},${y1} A ${r},${r} 0 ${largeArc},1 ${x2},${y2} Z`;
  const svg = d3.create("svg").attr("width", w).attr("height", h)
    .style("background", "#fafafa").style("border", "1px solid #ddd");
  // full circle outline
  svg.append("circle").attr("cx", cx).attr("cy", cy).attr("r", r)
    .attr("fill", "none").attr("stroke", "#bbb");
  // sector
  svg.append("path").attr("d", path).attr("fill", "rgba(38,102,170,0.25)")
    .attr("stroke", "#26a").attr("stroke-width", 2);
  // text
  const area = Math.PI * rad * rad * (secAngle / 360);
  const arcLen = 2 * Math.PI * rad * (secAngle / 360);
  svg.append("text").attr("x", 10).attr("y", 16).attr("font-size", 12)
    .text(`Sector area = (θ/360°) · πr² = ${area.toFixed(2)} cm²`);
  svg.append("text").attr("x", 10).attr("y", 32).attr("font-size", 12)
    .text(`Arc length  = (θ/360°) · 2πr = ${arcLen.toFixed(2)} cm`);
  return svg.node();
}






A sector is a fraction of the whole circle. The fraction is \theta/360°. Drag — when \theta = 360°, you get the whole circle.

