A car drives along a straight road. Its position at time t seconds is s(t) = t^2 metres.

Average speed from t = 1 to t = 3: (9 - 1)/(3 - 1) = 4 m/s.
From t = 1 to t = 1.5: (2.25 - 1)/0.5 = 2.5 m/s.
From t = 1 to t = 1.01: (1.0201 - 1)/0.01 = 2.01 m/s.
From t = 1 to t = 1.0001: ≈ 2.0001 m/s.

The values converge to 2 — the instantaneous speed at t = 1.
The widget below shrinks the time interval and shows the average speed approaching the slope of the tangent line.

viewof hVal = Inputs.range([0.001, 1], {value: 0.5, step: 0.001, label: "h (interval width)"})







{
  const t = 1, h = hVal;
  const s = t =&gt; t * t;
  const avg = (s(t + h) - s(t)) / h;
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;line-height:1.7;"&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;s(t) = t²&lt;/b&gt;, evaluating at t = 1, h = ${h.toFixed(4)}.&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Average rate: (s(1+h) − s(1))/h = &lt;b&gt;${avg.toFixed(6)}&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-top:0.4em;color:#666;"&gt;
      As h → 0, this approaches &lt;b&gt;2&lt;/b&gt; = ds/dt at t = 1.
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






The instantaneous rate of change is the limit of the average rate. That’s the derivative.

Touch
Write Pascal’s triangle. Start with a 1 at the top. Each row begins and ends with 1; every interior entry is the sum of the two entries above it.
                1
              1   1
            1   2   1
          1   3   3   1
        1   4   6   4   1
      1   5  10  10   5   1
    1   6  15  20  15   6   1
The n-th row is the list of \binom{n}{0}, \binom{n}{1}, \ldots,
\binom{n}{n}. And those are exactly the coefficients in the expansion of (a+b)^n.
The widget below expands (a + b)^n for any n you choose.

viewof bn = Inputs.range([1, 8], {value: 4, step: 1, label: "n"})







{
  // build (a+b)^n
  function fact(n) { let r = 1; for (let i = 2; i &lt;= n; i++) r *= i; return r; }
  function C(n, r) { return fact(n) / (fact(r) * fact(n - r)); }
  const terms = [];
  for (let r = 0; r &lt;= bn; r++) {
    const c = C(bn, r);
    const aPow = bn - r === 0 ? "" : (bn - r === 1 ? "a" : `a^${bn - r}`);
    const bPow = r === 0 ? "" : (r === 1 ? "b" : `b^${r}`);
    const coef = c === 1 ? "" : `${c}`;
    let term = coef + aPow + bPow;
    if (term === "") term = "1";
    terms.push(term);
  }
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;line-height:1.7;"&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;(a + b)&lt;sup&gt;${bn}&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/b&gt; =&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div style="font-size:1.1em;margin-left:1em;"&gt;${terms.join(" + ")}&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






Note how the powers of a go from n down to 0, the powers of b go from 0 up to n, and the coefficients trace exactly Pascal’s n-th row.

