Pile up unit cubes into a square of side n. The number of cubes is n^2. Now stack: a 1 \times 1 on top of 2 \times 2 on top of 3 \times 3 on top of \cdots on top of n \times n. The total cubes used is 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + \cdots + n^2.
Is there a clean formula? Yes — and the widget below verifies it for each n.

viewof Nss = Inputs.range([1, 20], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "n"})







{
  const n = Nss;
  let s1 = 0, s2 = 0, s3 = 0;
  for (let k = 1; k &lt;= n; k++) { s1 += k; s2 += k * k; s3 += k * k * k; }
  const f1 = n * (n + 1) / 2;
  const f2 = n * (n + 1) * (2 * n + 1) / 6;
  const f3 = (n * (n + 1) / 2) ** 2;
  return html`&lt;div style="font-family:system-ui;line-height:1.7;"&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;Σk&lt;/b&gt; = 1 + 2 + ... + ${n} = &lt;b&gt;${s1}&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp; (formula: n(n+1)/2 = ${f1})&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;Σk²&lt;/b&gt; = 1² + 2² + ... + ${n}² = &lt;b&gt;${s2}&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp; (formula: n(n+1)(2n+1)/6 = ${f2})&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;b&gt;Σk³&lt;/b&gt; = 1³ + 2³ + ... + ${n}³ = &lt;b&gt;${s3}&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp; (formula: [n(n+1)/2]² = ${f3})&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div style="margin-top:0.4em;color:#666;"&gt;
      Notice: Σk³ = (Σk)². The cubes' sum is the square of the linear sum.
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;
}






