Name

Compound angle (must memorise): \sin(A \pm B) = \sin A \cos B \pm \cos A \sin B \cos(A \pm B) = \cos A \cos B \mp \sin A \sin B \tan(A \pm B) = \frac{\tan A \pm \tan B}{1 \mp \tan A \tan B}
Double angle: \sin 2A = 2 \sin A \cos A \cos 2A = \cos^2 A - \sin^2 A = 1 - 2\sin^2 A = 2\cos^2 A - 1 \tan 2A = \frac{2\tan A}{1 - \tan^2 A}
Triple angle: \sin 3A = 3\sin A - 4\sin^3 A, \quad \cos 3A = 4\cos^3 A - 3\cos A
Half angle: \sin^2(\theta/2) = \tfrac{1-\cos\theta}{2}, \quad \cos^2(\theta/2) = \tfrac{1+\cos\theta}{2}
Sum to product: \sin C + \sin D = 2 \sin\tfrac{C+D}{2}\cos\tfrac{C-D}{2} \sin C - \sin D = 2 \cos\tfrac{C+D}{2}\sin\tfrac{C-D}{2} \cos C + \cos D = 2 \cos\tfrac{C+D}{2}\cos\tfrac{C-D}{2} \cos C - \cos D = -2 \sin\tfrac{C+D}{2}\sin\tfrac{C-D}{2}

A short verse:

Sin of a sum is sin-cos plus cos-sin; Cos of a sum has the minus locked in. Double the angle: two sin cos go free; Halve and a one minus cos lights the way.

