The number 30. List all its divisors: 1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 15,
30. Eight numbers. The structure of those divisors is hidden in the prime factorisation 30 = 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 5.

viewof n = Inputs.range([2, 100], {value: 30, step: 1, label: "n"})







{
  const divisors = [];
  for (let d = 1; d &lt;= n; d++) if (n % d === 0) divisors.push(d);
  let m = n, factors = {};
  let p = 2;
  while (m &gt; 1) {
    while (m % p === 0) { factors[p] = (factors[p] || 0) + 1; m /= p; }
    p++;
  }
  const fs = Object.entries(factors).map(([p, e]) =&gt; e === 1 ? p : `${p}^${e}`).join(" · ");
  return `**${n}**

Divisors (${divisors.length}): ${divisors.join(", ")}.

Prime factorisation: **${fs}**.`;
}






The number of divisors equals the product of (exponent + 1) over all primes — for 30 = 2^1 \cdot 3^1 \cdot 5^1, that’s 2 \cdot 2
\cdot 2 = 8.

